Here's an example of a function that returns a string containing HTML markup based on the given markdown text string:

```C++
std::string to_html(const std::string& markdown_text) {
    // split markdown text into lines using newline character
    std::vector<std::string> lines = split(markdown_text, "\n");

    // for each line, get the markdown syntax and escape html characters
    std::string html_text = "";
    for (const auto& line : lines) {
        std::string md_syntax = line;
        md_syntax = md_syntax.replace(":", "&#58;"); // backslash in front of : will escape it in html code
        md_syntax = md_syntax.replace("*", "&#124;"); // asterisk is also an html character, so replace it with |
        md_syntax = md_syntax.replace("-", "&#45;"); // hyphen is also an html character, so replace it with -

        // append the html syntax and any other text to the output string
        html_text += "<p>" + md_syntax + "</p>";
    }

    return html_text; // return the final string with html markup for each line in markdown text.
}
```
This function takes in a string containing markdown text and returns a new string containing the HTML markup based on that text. The first step is to split the input string into lines using the newline character, and then loop through each line of the markdown text. For each line, the function gets the markdown syntax by replacing any special characters like backslashes, asterisks, or hyphens with their HTML counterparts. The markdown syntax is then appended to a new output string, which contains HTML markup for each line in the input markdown text. The final output is returned as a string containing all of the HTML markup for the given markdown text.

